Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Colombia. The Colombian government has declared a health emergency and introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
For information on how to return to the UK from Colombia, see Return to the UK
Entry and borders
Colombiaâ€™s land and sea borders are now closed, including the border with Ecuador. Airports will close to international traffic from midnight on Monday 23 March. Thereafter no-one will be permitted to enter, for a provisional period of 30 days.
These regulations are subject to change at short notice and you should check with your travel provider before your journey.
All national or foreign citizens who intend to enter the country should complete the Preventive Control Against Coronavirus form.
Cruise ships are not being allowed to dock at Colombian ports.
Ecuador has closed its border to arrivals from Colombia though is currently allowing people to leave. You should monitor local authority statements on social media (@Migracioncol). The Colombian border with Venezuela is now closed.
Local measures
All gatherings of more than 500 people have been cancelled.
President Duque announced a State of Emergency on 18 March, announcing new measures including nationwide mandatory self-isolation for anyone over the age of 70, from 20 March to 31 May.
President Duque further announced on 20 March that nationwide isolation measures would be in effect from 11.59pm on 24 March, until 13 April. These measures restrict social contact and movement to essential activities only (which would include obtaining food supplies and access to medical services).
Regional authorities are implementing significant further measures, which include curfews. Check local news and the British Embassy Twitter page (updates in English).
Further information
If you present symptoms in Colombia, you should contact your heath care provider or call the national healthline for coronavirus on 018000- 955590 or (57-1) 3305041 in Bogota (in Spanish). For further information, please check the Ministry of Health website and/or social media channels (@MinSaludCol).
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
